node.text:
I honestly still can’t believe it. Just 2 years ago I was a totally unknown girl from a tiny town in the mountains of California, pursuing a record because I loved to travel and had the faint dream to one day spend my life sharing our world with others.

I'm very grateful to each you for sharing your time with me. You have given me a platform and a voice and I wish I could thank each of you face to face because you guys are now what inspires me each day! For those of you who have found me more recently, I want to take the opportunity to explain in this video how our community has grown over the past few years❤️

After fasting even for one day, I’ve learned that Ramadan is about so much more than fasting. It’s about becoming aware of your negative habits and practicing self control. It’s a time dedicated towards prayer, reflection and meditation. It teaches you to be grateful for all the blessings in your life and to be more understanding towards people less fortunate than you. 
It’s also about community. It’s taking the time away from your normal routine to disconnect and come together to share meals and appreciate each other’s presence in our lives. 
Thank you to @ammar for sharing your perspective with me during this amazing experience. I’m feeling very grateful for the opportunity to learn more about Islamic culture and to those of you who are fasting this month, Ramadan Mubarak!

node.text: Looking back, we've had a really good first year together. On paper, our schedules made it feel impossible to make a relationship work. To our surprise, we really made the most out of very little downtime and even got to travel to 8 countries together this year!! Our adventures have been so exciting but I like the simple takeout & movie nights in Venice just as much. Thanks for keeping me entertained with all 264 of the voices in your head, for always being patient and kind, and for bringing me coffee in bed every morning. Jag älskar dig 😘

node.text: This trip to Pakistan was such an honor to be apart of and it represents so many of my beliefs about the world. There is power in positive tourism. When people to travel to countries that have been portrayed negatively in the media, it begins to break down the barriers created between us. It’s hard to be close minded when you get the opportunity to meet real people and experience the beauty of these lesser known places for yourself✨ #PakistanZindabad

The tank graveyard outside Asmara, Eritrea is full of old military vehicles that were used during the 30 year war between Eritrea and Ethiopia. 
They’ve stacked up the old, rusted scrap metal here as a reminder to the Eritrean people of the sacrifices that were made to free their nation. 
What do you think of my first adventure vlog? Let me know in the comments!

node.text:
See ya later, USA!✈️ 

Josh Homme once told Anthony Bourdain, "Nothing feels better than going home, and nothing feels better than leaving home — the bittersweet curse." 

& I couldn't agree more 😅

Travel is my favorite catalyst for change because it's nearly impossible to grow stagnant while you're on an adventure. However, I also cherish having time at home to slow down and rest. Travel has also made me appreciate being home in a way that I wouldn't have discovered if I never left. 

Lately I've been trying find that spark that only new experiences bring, even on the most mundane days. It's made me realize there's always something new to explore, even close to home. My new goal is to maintain that same sense of excitement whenever I am in the world!😆 

Next stop, France 🇫🇷

I Trained Like Wonder Woman for 30 Days is now LIVE on Youtube! 

Wonder Woman is one of the most iconic superheroes of all time. Ever since I was a little girl, I was inspired by this empowering character that symbolizes a smart, strong female who isn’t afraid to take action even in the face of danger or despair.    The Wonder Woman character has evolved much in the last 80 years, but most recently the role has been played by Gal Gadot. To prepare her for taking on this role that has pushed her into global superstardom, Gal Gadot was trained by my good friend @magnuslygdback for months both before and during the filming of Wonder Woman. It wasn’t until my team and I created this short action scene that I realized just how intensely actors and actresses need to train to be strong enough to make these movie moments come to life!

Click the link in my bio to watch the full training video!!

I want to say a huge THANK YOU to all my amazing friends who contributed to this project. This was by far my biggest production yet and I’m so grateful to be able to collaborate with so many creative people.

Lately I’ve been finding scraps of inspiration in my camera roll that bring waves of nostalgia rolling back into the spotlight. Actual footage of me trying to figure out how to afford to travel🥴

Being frugal was the secret to my success! I've eaten 1-2 meals for $7/day and I've staying in bug infested hostels for $2. I've hitchhiked, slept on floors and taken 12+ hour bus rides. 

Before I started creating travel content, I was figuring out to budget my trips one week at a time. I worked multiple jobs while going to school and saved every dollar I made for 6 years because I dreamed of taking a gap year to travel the world. As you may know already, that gap year I took at 18 years old sparked my goal of traveling to every country. 

For the first few years, the most I could travel was 1.5-2 months then I had to come back to California to work because I hadn't quite figured out how to monetize my passion for travel. At the time I had a lot of odd jobs but I was mainly working at my family’s travel agency and running my own private chauffeuring service. I was posting on social media for fun but I didn't believe that I could actually make money doing that. Once I saved up enough cash, hotel points and airline miles, I would start traveling again.

Then I hit a wall. The countries I needed to travel to were becoming too expensive and I couldn't keep up. I was flat broke and out of options. I only had about 3,000 followers but through some key connections and divine timing, I somehow picked up my first major brand deal (thanks @moncler ). The money I made from that job was enough to finance my trip around 10+ countries in West/Central Africa which was a crucial aspect of traveling to every country. After that first job, everything changed for me. I fell in love with telling stories, eventually found YouTube, and the rest is history. 

What worked for me may be different for you. Travelers are some of the most financially creative people because there are so many ways to fund your adventures. After all these crazy experiences I’ve learned tons of financial lessons the hard way as a solo female traveler and I’m excited to start teaching you guys more about everything I’ve learned along the way!

The BEST part of travel is the PEOPLE we meet along the way...

The tribes living in the Omo Vally in Southern Ethiopia have maintained their traditional practices, close familial ties, vibrant community life, deep connection to nature, and contentment without materialism in the midst of a modern world. Sitting beneath the open canopy roofs, I was able to meet so many people who, even though we didn’t share the same language, were open to sharing their home and their culture. 

They adorn their bodies with paint, gauges, jewelry and leather pelts. Men carry AK 47s not only for protection but as a status symbol worthy of marriage. They drink fermented sorghum beer when they’re celebrating and slaughter enough cows for a feast when a boy becomes a man. For special occasions like Ukuli Bula, the bull jumping ceremony, Hamer women compliment their traditional regalia with bells around their legs and also play horns when dancing and singing together.

Living with a Remote African Tribe for 24 Hours is live on Youtube if you want to see my full story about the Hamer Tribe!

Cover photo by @storiesmatter with @abyssiniannomads

Only 5% of the entire world’s population today still live in a tribal society. 

These tribes’ homes and ways of life are undergoing constant change from globalization and many of these tribes are closed to outsiders. However, some tribes welcome visitors and one of these is the Hamer Tribe of Ethiopia, famous for its centuries-old coming of age ceremony where its warriors jump across live bulls.

One of the main purposes of travel is to experience the lives of people with different viewpoints from your own in order to gain new perspectives of how fellow humans do this thing called life. These experiences may either challenge or reinforce your existing viewpoint and what I can say for certain is that I will never forget what I experienced here in the Omo Valley.

Living for 24 Hours with the Bull Jumping Tribe is now live on Youtube! This is the Ethiopia series finale and I am so proud of the stories we were able to tell in this beautiful country. What was your favorite video in the series?!

I would love to hear your thoughts in the comments! 🌍

Raise your hand if you're ready for a European summer🙌🏼 

This is a photo dump from a trip to Europe I took during the summer of 2016. The trip that started it all🤩 I had just graduated from college and I was embarking on a year of travel that I had been saving up to go on for 6 years. My friends and I backpacked through the Swiss Alps, bungee jumped for the first time and explored castles in Germany. We ate endless cheese, baguettes & wine on a $10/day food budget. I met some of the kindest travelers of my life in Italy who remain our friends to this day. Every place was so new and exciting but I think it was our mindset that made it such an unforgettable experience. We were traveling for the simple joy of it. We weren't going places just to take photos or to compare our adventure to others. I felt so present every day, my eyes were eager to soak up every new piece of information in the world around me. THAT is the energy I want to feel this summer 😆

I'm excited to be traveling around Europe again soon, where do you think I should go this time?!

Wandering through the ancient tunnels surrounding the Lalibela churches has been on my bucket list for ages. When travel and history intertwine I'm always filled with so much wonder and excitement, especially in a place as mysterious as Lalibela. 

While exploring this place I wanted to tell the story of the Ark of the Covenant and it's fascinating connection to Ethiopia. There’s no other culture in the world that has a living history of worshiping the Ark of the Covenant which insinuates that there’s a deeper relationship here. I'm not going to argue fact or fiction or theory, but there are many historians who dismiss this Ethiopian version of the story due to lack of tangible evidence to prove it. The void of evidence about the Ark of the Covenant’s fate is so complete that Stephen Spielberg could send Indiana Jones on a fictional quest for it halfway around the world without much fear of contradicting any established wisdom. 

I'm proud to say this YouTube video ignites the same sense of adventure that I had as a little kid watching Raiders of the Lost Ark with my dad. You're never too old to make your childhood daydreams a reality😆

Click the link in my bio to watch the video now!

A mysterious city, carved from the bedrock of time itself. This is a place where every corner seems to hold ancient secrets. During my recent trip to Lalibela, I discovered a legend that a holy relic had been hidden in these mountains of Ethiopia for centuries⏳  The whereabouts of the lost Ark of the Covenant has eluded scholars and archaeologists, kings and world leaders, for thousands of years. Many have thought that if they could control it, they could control supernatural powers. Its location is a mystery that has swept the globe as some say that the Ark of the Covenant was destroyed long ago by an invading army, but others say that it was hidden away and survives to the present day… 

Check out the full video from this adventure is now on Youtube to find out more!😆 link in bio

A special thanks to @cory.s.martin @storiesmatter @johnyurei  @stevenjeastwood @sydwaitforitney 
and @abyssiniannomads for helping me bring this story to life! This is one of my absolute favorite episodes I’ve ever created and it wouldn’t have been possible without each of them🙌🏼

The church of Saint George is one of eleven rock churches here in Lalibela. Each church was made by carving into the soft volcanic tufa rock of the mountain from the top down and then tunneling inside to make the rooms and windows and decorations. From its beginning, Lalibela was one of the holiest places to the Ethiopian Orthodox Church and hundreds of thousands of pilgrims still come here each year as they have been doing for centuries. 

I was fortunate enough to be able to sit down with the priest who has served at St. George’s Church for decades. His name is Kis Derbe and it was incredible to be able to learn more about the Ark of the Covenant’s connection to Lalibela from his perspective.
